[3] Argentina
Date: Thu 30 Mar 2006
From: Alfonso Rodriguez <ajrm_msds@yahoo.es>
Source: Linea Capital, Argentina, 29 Mar 2006 [translated by Mod.JGM, edited]
<http://www.lineacapital.com.ar/?noticia=8546>

3 cases of dengue fever were confirmed in Puerto Iguazu. For 5 years, no
dengue fever transmission has been reported in Misiones.
The affected persons, 2 adults and a child, are members of the same family.
Their blood samples had been sent to Pergamino Institute in order to
identify the causative agent/strain and the definitive diagnosis.
The Provincial Epidemiology Direction detected and confirmed 3 dengue fever
cases in Puerto Iguazu, 2 adults and one child; all of them are members of
the same family. Misiones province had no patients infected with dengue
fever virus since the last epidemic outbreak that occurred back in 2001.
"Three years ago, we had 2 dengue fever cases, but they were foreign, since
these patients got infected in Rio de Janeiro, and this might not have
happened with the 3 cases detected last week in Iguazu, since they seem to
be locally acquired cases," confirmed the Epidemiology Director, Dr. Julio
Roberto Estevez.
According to this officer, blood samples from the 3 persons affected by
dengue fever in Puerto Iguazu had already been reported as positive in the
1st 2 diagnostic studies performed in the province. "Now we are waiting for
the results of Pergamino National Institute for Virology in Buenos Aires
province in order to determine the causative strain. We are also analyzing
samples from other suspected cases who have the typical symptoms of the
disease (muscle pain, headache and flu-like illness without sneezing), but
until now, all of them had been reported as negative."
Meanwhile, according to routine procedures, before diagnoses were confirmed
in Puerto Iguazu, healthcare personnel from the Public Health Ministry
performed environmental control actions and household and surrounding areas
fumigation in areas near SAMIC Hospital in Puerto Iguazu (where the
affected family lives) and searched for other suspect febrile cases.
Environmental control actions were also performed within the property of
the affected family, a few kilometers from Puerto Iguazu, and blood samples
were taken from neighbors who declared they had had fever within the past
15 days.
"This disease had never gone away. Dengue is currently in our country, and
in Misiones, it never went away after the year 2001, and even infestation
levels (mosquito vector population density) are very high throughout the
province. For some reason that still is [obscure] for me, until now we did
not have native cases in the province, but both in Paraguay and Brazil,
cases were still being detected," pointed out Dr. Estevez.
In fact, yesterday [28 Mar 2006], Dr. Vilma Basualdo, head of Health
Surveillance in Paraguay, confirmed the occurrence of 9 cases of dengue
fever in Asuncion, specifically in La Encarnacion neighborhood, where other
suspected cases were analyzed, so she estimated that there may be at least
30 cases.
Meanwhile, in Foz de Iguazu (Brazil), the existence of an important
transmission focus was confirmed, and 150 cases have been detected since
last week. Also, in Rio de Janeiro 100 affected persons were diagnosed in
the past few days.
"Climate these days does not help at all; we are in summer season and with
plenty of rainfall favoring the reproduction of the mosquito vector.
Certainly, I consider that there had been no more recent cases in the
region, since even though high temperatures were recorded, it was
accompanied by drought," he [Estevez] pointed out.
Dengue fever becomes evident after a one week incubation period, "and,
according to its symptoms, many persons call it "dry flu." Affected persons
must not take aspirin, since it may favor hemorrhagic complications; they
should use paracetamol instead; they must urgently seek medical care, and
they must inform the physician about any trip to neighboring countries,"
said Dr. Estevez.
Dengue is an infectious disease transmitted by _Aedes aegypti_ mosquitos.
Therefore, the main preventive measure is to eliminate all breeding sites
for mosquitoes, water in any type of container, even flower pots and old tires.
"The problem is that neighbors in general do know preventive measures, but
they do not incorporate them within their habits. Another pitfall is that
municipalities must not abandon their responsibility with respect to basic
environmental sanitation, but, in real life, because of lack of resources
or because they have other priorities to take care of, most of them do not
perform environmental sanitation activities," said Dr. Estevez, the
Epidemiology Director. He said that "we have to understand that dengue
fever prevention is a priority in Misiones, a province where winter exists
only when you look at almanacs."
--
