[4] Paraguay
Date: 28 Mar 2006
From: Alfonso Rodriguez <ajrm_msds@yahoo.es>
Source: ABC Digital, Paraguay, 28 Mar 2006 [translated by Mod.JGM, edited]
<http://www.abc.com.py>

There is an epidemiological alert in Asuncion now that there are more
confirmed cases of dengue fever. The Health (Ministry) is concerned that
the hemorrhagic form may spread.
Health Surveillance General Direction at the Ministry of Public Health
declared yesterday [27 Mar 2006] an epidemiological alert in Asuncion and
in all Paraguayan borders now that 10 cases were confirmed as positive for
dengue fever in the capital city.
"There is a risk that an epidemic with unpredictable consequences may
occur, so we are urging people to make every effort to prevent it," says
the 2nd bulletin issued to all hospitals in the country.
The 10 confirmed cases occurred in Loma Pyta (15 minutes distance from
Asuncion), and there was another case in Nuestra Se ra del Huerto
neighborhood in Itauguay, and the other 7 cases occurred in La Encarnacion,
where this outbreak started.
Minister of Health Dr. Teresa Leon said in a press conference that they are
concerned because of the likelihood of an epidemic outbreak, particularly
with respect to hemorrhagic dengue fever cases, considering that there are
more than 20 000 susceptible persons that may acquire dengue hemorrhagic
fever, which is the most severe form of the disease.
With respect to the single case registered in Itaugu city (27 km from
Asuncion), she expressed that there are no persons with fever around the
house of the affected 11-year old boy.
What concerns health authorities is the situation in La Encarnacion
neighborhood, where 7 cases had been confirmed.
Meanwhile, there are another 30 suspected cases that will be confirmed or
ruled out during this week. Dr. Leon recommended that if early symptoms
appear (high fever, muscle pain, and retro-ocular pain), persons must go to
physicians and not self-medicate, since many people take aspirin, which may
be harmful. She admitted that there is fear because of the possible
occurrence of dengue hemorrhagic fever, "since we already had serotype one
all over the country; even though we still do not know what serotype is
currently circulating, there is always a risk for the development of
hemorrhagic dengue fever," she declared.
Considering that heavy rainfalls are occurring, Dr. Leon said that all
rubbish in yards must be disposed of, particularly flower pots, containers,
bottles, and anything that may accumulate rainfall water, since this water
serves as a mosquito breeding site.
"Nowadays, the main priority in our country is that the disease must not
spread, since it leads to school and job absenteeism; remember we had a
serious epidemic back in 2000," added Dr. Leon.
On the other hand, a mother, a neighbor in la Encarnacion, complained that
her daughter-in-law, 40-years-old, has all the dengue fever symptoms, but
to date, no healthcare personnel from the 18th Sanitary Region has been to
her household to administer medications to the patient.
SENEPA (Paraguayan National Malaria Eradication Service), as part of the
fight against dengue fever, recommends the following:
* Allow healthcare personnel and officers to enter households, these
persons will be adequately identified and accredited.
* This personnel will capture _Aedes_ mosquito larvae.
* They will identify possible mosquito breeding sites, and they will teach
persons how to eliminate and destroy these breeding sites.
* Cooperation is requested in order to eliminate all water-containing
recipients (paint cans, tin cans, old toys, plastic recipients, and the like).
* Notification of febrile patients can be made calling 215-168/9 and 203-998.
--
