[5] Bolivia
Date: Tue 28 Mar 2006
From: Alfonso Rodriguez <ajrm_msds@yahoo.es>
Source: Los Tiempos, Bolivia, 28 Mar 2006 [translated by Mod.JGM, edited]
<http://www.lostiempos.com>

4 cases of dengue fever are reported in the tropics, 86 suspected cases as
of March 2006
-----------------------------------------------
Health personnel reported the occurrence of 4 cases of classic dengue fever
in 3 communities in tropical Cochabamba in the 1st quarter of 2006.
The Departmental Health Services (SEDES, according to its Spanish initials)
stated that the outbreak is well within the usual behavior of this tropical
disease, and it announced that they were sending healthcare worker teams to
the affected areas as a part of preventive measures.
According to the reports by healthcare personnel, it is known that 2 of the
confirmed dengue fever cases occurred in Ivirgarzama community, one in
Villa Tunari and the last one in Shinahota. Patients who were reported as
positive for dengue fever in laboratory tests were part of the 86 suspected
cases registered during the 1st quarter of 2006.
In the 2005 classic dengue outbreak (between June and November), 24
patients suspected to have dengue fever were reported out of a 350-person
possibly-infected-group, according to SEDES data. The most affected regions
in this outbreak were Shinahota and Ivirgarzama.
Now that there is a new outbreak, healthcare personnel said that next week
at least 10 teams will arrive at the affected area so that, in coordination
with local municipalities, breeding areas for the dengue fever vector,
_Aedes aegypti_ or other species, will be destroyed. Household fumigation
will take place only in the areas with a very high mosquito population.
SEDES director, Mr. Jaime Monta del Granado, said that sending teams to
Chapare is part of their routine activity and that dengue fever cases that
have been reported are well within the normal parameters for the disease.
--
