[6] Brazil
Date: Tue 28 Mar 2006
From: Alfonso Rodriguez <ajrm_msds@yahoo.es>
Source: Diariodepenapolis.com, Brazil, 28 Mar 2006 [translated by Mod.LJS,
edited]
<http://www.diariodepenapolis.com.br/site/2803/cid01.php>

Disease: 2 cases of dengue are reported in Penapolis
-----------------------------------------------
The Municipal Department of Health of Penapolis received yesterday [27 Mar
2006] the confirmation of 2 more cases of dengue in the town. With these,
the total number of cases in 2006 rises to 3; the 1st was on 27 Jan 2006.
According to the Town Hall Department of Social Communication, the affected
persons are adults, a man and a woman. One of the patients lives in the
rural area of the municipality, in the "bairro" Araponga and the other on
Dr. Mario Sabino Street, downtown.
The head of disease surveillance, Ms. Rosalicia Maria Lundstedt, R.N., says
that the routine measures of contact tracing and landscape managing have
already been undertaken. "We undertake these measures notwithstanding
confirmation. With the confirmation of these cases, what is left to do is
insecticide fogging to control adult mosquitoes in a radius of 200 meters
from the residencies of the cases. For this work, we have to wait for a
position from the Superintend cia de Controle de Endemias [the state
vector-borne disease control agency] that coordinates the actions and
supplies the insecticide, she said.
Rosalicia revealed that the town's situation is highly complicated. In the
Breteau index (which measures the infestation by the dengue vector
mosquito), between one and 3.9 is considered an alert. An index higher than
3.9 indicates the risk of an outbreak.
In the light of this we cannot deny that Penapolis will suffer problems
related to the occurrence of new cases, for there is an area of the town
that we call Area 2 that has a Breteau index of 5.14. This area comprises
the "bairros" of Vila Gardim, Vila Martins, S Vicente, Guanabara, Santa
Terezinha, Formosa, Primavera, Bairro Jardim, S Paulo, Residencial M io
Sabino, Residencial Fernanda, S Joaquim, Cidade Jardim, Jardim do Lago,
Vilage, Vilage Regina, Alto das Brisas, S Fernando, Palmares, Monreal, Del
Rey, Portal dos Faveiros, Miguel Barbeiro, Ana Paula and Regina C ia.
According to the last Breteau census, done last January [2005?], the area
called Area 1 (which comprises the "bairros" of Vila Anselmo, Vila F ima,
Vila Am ica, Vila Popular, Jardim Ip Jardim, Bras ia, Bela Vista, Jardim
Erc ia, Jardim Por do Sol, Distrito Industrial, Jardim Eldorado, Jardim
Canad, Vila T uio, Jardim Premier e Morumbi) has an index of 3.15. Area 3
(which comprises the "bairros" of S via Covas, Esplanada, Jardim dos
Sonhos, Residencial Dois Irm s, Morada do Sol, Menino Ariovaldo, Jardim
Para o, Atl tica, Tropical, Colina Verde, Haroldo Camilo, Parque dos Girass
s, Pereirinha, Aphaville, Panorana, Independ cia, Vila Aparecida, Ipiranga,
Planalto, Jardim Pevi, Rosa Alberton, Floren , Altimari, Edejama, Jardim
Paula Pereira, Shangri-le Vila Santos) has an index of 2.28.
These indexes are frightening. Rosalicia said that since 1999, the town did
not have such indexes. "I consider these indexes frightening, for they
reflect the lack of consciousness of the persons. The citizens are not
taking care of their backyards, since larvae were found in homes in several
bairros of the town." She emphasized that Area 2, particularly in the
neighborhood of Del Rey and Cidade Jardim, is totally infested.
"The highest tolerable index for a municipality is 1.99, [in order] to not
have dengue transmission," she explained. When the latest Breteau index
results were made public, Rosalicia called attention to the fact that
dengue cases should occur, since dengue virus 1, 2 and 3 circulate in the
municipality.
"For this reason [we] are under the risk of having hemorrhagic dengue in
Penapolis. We recommended that population be alerted to perform a search in
their backyards, removing everything that can hold water. But this has to
be done continuously, or what happens is that the town administration
performs a dragnet to remove water-holding objects, but sometime later the
backyards are again cluttered with these objects, making way for the female
mosquito to lay her eggs.
--
