[7] Venezuela
Date: Tue 28 Mar 2006
From: Alfonso Rodriguez <ajrm_msds@yahoo.es>
Source: Alerta Epidemiolico, Semana Epidemiologica 10, Ministerio de Salud,
Venezuela, 5-11 Mar 2006 [translated, edited]
<http://www.msds.gov.ve/msds/Boletines/Alertas/2006/Boletin10_2006.zip>

During the current epidemiologic week, 665 cases were diagnosed, of which
38 were hemorrhagic fever (5.7 percent), with a ratio of classic dengue /
hemorrhagic fever at 17:1. The accumulated cases of the year is running at
8277, of which 5.9 percent are hemorrhagic fever (487 cases), with a ratio
of classic dengue / hemorrhagic fever at 16:1. The rate of cumulative
morbidity is 31.1 per 100 000 inhabitants. The circulating serotypes of
dengue viruses are type: 1, 2, 3 and 4. The cases within the period have
increased by 31.5 percent with respect to the number of total cases in the
same period last year [2005] (6291 cases).
In the present week, no deaths caused by dengue were reported. An increase
of 6.7 percent in the number of cases with respect to the previous week was
registered, being considered a situation for alert. The population of 15
years of age and under comprises the highest, at 52.0 percent of the
notified total cases; the group between 15 to 24 years of age, at 23.0
percent, the next highest. The Federal offices have reported the places
with prominent numbers of cases as being: Zulia (112), M ida (55), Miranda
(54), Trujillo (53) and Lara (49).
